06920nam a22008055i 9780231552189DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315521897 a10.7312/berr197462doi  a(DE-B1597)627205  a(OCoLC)1309043511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS799.7b.M87 2022 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a951.249/0422304aThe Musha Incident :bA Reader on the Indigenous Uprising in Colonial Taiwan /ced. by Michael Berry. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b16 images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Chinese Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Romanization -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Approaching Musha -- tPART I Historical Memories of Musha -- tCHAPTER ONE The Discourse and Practice of Colonial “Suppression” in the Making of the Musha Rebellion and Its Aftermath -- tCHAPTER TWO The Musha Incident and the History of Tgdaya-Japanese Relations -- tCHAPTER THREE Relistening to Her and His Stories On Approaching “The Musha Incident from an Indigenous Perspective” -- tPART II Literary Memories of Musha -- tCHAPTER FOUR Bodies and Violence in the Musha Incident -- tCHAPTER FIVE Musha Incident, Incidentally: Tsushima Yūko’s Exceedingly Barbaric -- tCHAPTER SIX Satō Haruo on the Musha Incident -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Untimely Meditations: The Contemporary, the Philosophy of Walking, and Related Ethical Matters in Remains of Life -- tPART III Visual and Digital Memories of Musha -- tCHAPTER EIGHT The Face of the Inbetweener: The Image of Indigenous History Researchers as Reflected in Seediq Bale -- tCHAPTER NINE Quest for Roots: Trauma and Heroism in Wu He’s Yusheng and Tang Shiang-Chu’s Yusheng: Seediq Bale -- tCHAPTER TEN Historical Representation in an Age of Wiki Writing and Digital Curation: The Musha Incident on Digital Platforms -- tPART IV Musha in Cultural Dialogue -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN Fiction and Fieldwork: In Conversation with Wu He on Remains of Life -- tCHAPTER TWELVE Heavy Metal Headhunt: An Interview with Chthonic’s Freddy Lim -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN Televising the Musha Incident: Wan Jen on the Miniseries Dana Sakura -- tCHAPTER FOURTEEN No Good Guys or Bad Guys: An Interview with Wei Te-sheng -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn October 27, 1930, members of six Taiwanese indigenous groups ambushed the Japanese attendees of an athletic competition at the Musha Elementary School, killing 134. The uprising came as a shock to Japanese colonial authorities, whose response was swift and brutal. Heavy artillery and battalions of troops assaulted the region, spraying a wide area with banned poison gas. The Seediq from Mhebu, who led the uprising, were brought to the brink of genocide.Over the ensuing decades, the Musha Incident became seen as a central moment in Taiwan’s colonial history, and different political regimes and movements have seized on it for various purposes. Under the Japanese, it was used to attest to the “barbarity” of Taiwan’s indigenous tribes; the Nationalist regime cited the uprising as proof of the Taiwanese peoples’ heroism and solidarity with the Chinese in resisting the Japanese; and pro-independence groups in Taiwan have portrayed the Seediq people and their history as exemplars of Taiwan’s “authentic” cultural traditions, which stand apart from that of mainland China.This book brings together leading scholars to provide new perspectives on one of the most traumatic episodes in Taiwan’s modern history and its fraught legacies. Contributors from a variety of disciplines revisit the Musha Incident and its afterlife in history, literature, film, art, and popular culture. They unravel the complexities surrounding it by confronting a history of exploitation, contradictions, and misunderstandings. The book also features conversations with influential cultural figures in Taiwan who have attempted to tell the story of the uprising.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHistory in popular culturezTaiwan. 0aMusha Rebellion, 1930xHistoriography. 0aMusha Rebellion, 1930. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aBarclay, Paul D, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChing, Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiu, Kuei-fen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEki Pacidal, Nakao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKitamura, Kae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiao, Ping-hui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRayns, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Toulouse-Antonin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSterk, Darryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTierney, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWu, Chien-heng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/berr1974640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231552189423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231552189/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PP